<h2>Event in March 2019</h2>
<br><br>
<strong>Avalanches</strong>
<br><br>
During the winter months, there was a lot of snowfall in Europe, especially in the Alps. With higher temperatures in March the snowpack becomes unstable which can lead to avalanches. In fact the frozen precipitation is suddenly re-distributed and these dangerous events cause damage and loss of lifes. Avalanches were reported in Switzerland, Austria, but also in Scotland and Norway.
<br><br>
<strong> Severe storms</strong>
<br><br>
At the beginning of March, several storm lows swept across Europe in succession. Above all, the United Kingdom, Ireland, the Benelux countries and Germany were affected. Winterstorm Alexander first swept with gusts up to 181 kph on 02 March 2019 over the UK. Two days later, Bennet followed, that also produced gusts up to 144 kph in Germany.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/mar2019/Karten2019_20190306sat111s.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/mar2019/Karten2019_20190306sat111s.jpg" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1 Visible satellite image of Alexander during 02 March 2019 (Source:NASA )</em>
<br><br>
On the backside of Bennet several squall lines formed over Germany, which also had heavy storm gusts. Directly after Bennet the depression Cornelius followed. After the storm series during early March another series came directly after the first. This consisted of five winterstorms which moved successively from March 10 to March 17 over Europe and Germany. The depression Eberhard was the first one with gusts up to 166 kph,
followed by Franz (126 kph) and Gebhard II (130 kph). The storms Heinz and Igor formed the conclusion of the storm series. The storms not only brought destructive winds but also severe precipitation, for Gebhard as deep as 100 mm in 24 hours in the Black Forest.
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for March 2019</h2>
<br><br>
<strong>Less frost days in the east</strong>
<br><br>
The prevailing westerly flow from the North Atlantic brought mild air quite far into eastern parts of Europe. Cold air outbreaks from the northeast were largely missing. This caused a much lower number of frost days than usual especially in large parts of Eastern Europe (Figure 2).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/mar2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_FD_baselayers_overlay_2019-03-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/mar2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_FD_baselayers_overlay_2019-03-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
