<a href="../images/mar2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc__2019-03-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/mar2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_fd_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc__2019-03-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Number of frost days (FD) in March 2019 (left) and anomaly w.r.t. 1981-2010 (right)</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
<strong>Dry in the south, wet in the north, but heavy precipitation was rare</strong>
<br><br>
While many parts of Southern Europe were quite dry for this time in the year, much of Central and Northern Europe received more precipitation than normal (Figure 3). This was due to a large number of low pressure systems moving mostly over the North and Baltic Sea from west to east. Especially in Ireland, much of the UK and northern Germany most of the month was rainy. However, days with heavy rain (above 10 or 20mm) were quite rare except some places (Figure 4). In the first half of the month, storms moved very quickly over Europe without dropping much rain locally. Later in the month, high pressure influence increased in Central Europe and rain systems were further in the north and relatively weak.
<br><br>
